            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Park\u2019s story is one of quiet rebellion. Raised in the tech-saturated suburbs of San Jose, he was the only son of first-generation Korean immigrants who equated success with engineering degrees and stock options. His parents, a software developer and a lab technician, couldn't understand his childhood fascination with the brushstrokes in a coffee table book on Van Gogh or his insistence on visiting museums instead of science fairs. For them, art was a hobby, not a livelihood.\n\nHis choice to study Art History at UCLA was a source of immense family tension. It felt like a deliberate rejection of their hard-earned American dream. David, however, saw it as claiming his own. He excelled, finding a language for the beauty and context he\u2019d always felt intuitively. He pursued his Master\u2019s at San Francisco State University, drawn to the city's vibrant and defiant arts scene. After a series of internships and assistant roles, he landed his current position as an Exhibitions Manager at a prominent museum near Civic Center.\n\nA key turning point came three years ago when he managed a major retrospective for a groundbreaking Korean-American video artist. Seeing his parents walk through the gallery, reading the name \"David Park\" in the exhibition catalog, and listening to the critical acclaim, he finally felt a sense of validation. It was a bridge between their world and his.\n\nToday, David lives in a sleek one-bedroom apartment in Hayes Valley with his partner, a landscape architect named Michael. His 2.8-mile commute on the MUNI is a cherished ritual, a time to listen to podcasts on curatorial theory or simply watch the city wake up. His days are a whirlwind of budgets, artist logistics, and installation plans\u2014the practical scaffolding that allows art to shine. He loves his neighborhood's proximity to the opera and symphony, and its blend of chic boutiques and enduring character.\n\nDavid\u2019s dream is to one day become a Chief Curator, shaping an institution's vision and championing underrepresented artists. He wants to ensure that other kids, especially those from immigrant backgrounds, see their stories and heritage reflected on gallery walls, not just as a hobby, but as a vital part of the cultural conversation."
