            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, cross-legged on the beige suburban carpet, the Van Gogh coffee table book open across his lap. His parents\u2019 voices drifted from the kitchen, a familiar murmur of silicon and lab results. But David heard nothing, his finger tracing the thick, churning impasto of *The Starry Night* printed on the glossy page. This felt more real, more structural than any microchip. It was a silent, deeply personal discovery of another world, a secret language he knew he had to learn. This moment planted the seed of his quiet rebellion.\n\n2.\nDuring his sophomore year at UCLA, a professor deconstructed Goya's *The Third of May, 1808*, speaking not of its beauty, but of its power as political testimony. In the dark lecture hall, a switch flipped in David\u2019s mind. The fight with his parents wasn't just about choosing paintings over programming; it was about choosing a different kind of consequence. Art wasn\u2019t a frivolous escape. It was a record, a weapon, a form of truth. That day, his passion gained a purpose beyond his own fascination.\n\n3.\nHis first week as a Master\u2019s student at SFSU, he rode the MUNI K-Ingleside outbound, getting intentionally lost. As the streetcar lurched above ground near West Portal, the city\u2019s unique, layered architecture spread out below him. It wasn't the manicured landscape of his youth, but a chaotic, vibrant, living installation. He felt a profound sense of arrival, not just in a new city, but in a place that matched the energy of the art he loved. He knew then he wouldn't leave.\n\n4.\nThe museum\u2019s loading dock, five years ago. An installation piece, a fragile sculpture of hand-blown glass, arrived with a hairline fracture. The artist was frantic, the curator despondent. David, then just an assistant, spent the next hour sourcing a specialized epoxy and steadying the artist\u2019s hand as they performed the delicate repair. In the quiet satisfaction of that save, he found his calling\u2014not just loving art, but being the calm, practical scaffold that allows it to stand. It secured his identity within the art world.\n\n5.\nHe remembers their first proper date at the SF Botanical Garden. Michael, then a stranger he\u2019d met through friends, stopped and explained the design of the New Zealand cloud forest collection\u2014how it replicated an ecosystem through deliberate choices of slope, shade, and species. He spoke of sightlines and soil composition with the same reverence David reserved for exhibition lighting. David felt a jolt of recognition. Michael didn\u2019t just tolerate his world; he understood the architecture of beauty. He felt, for the first time, truly home with someone."
